    "type": "Question",
    "name": "Question 29 @ 2018/2019",
    "Question": {
      "content": "A small copper plate has a mass of 3g, the atomic number of Cu is 29 and the mass number is 63.5g/mol. What is the total charge of all electrons in the plate?",
      "type": "OBJ",
      "options": [
        "24.8×10²C",
        "2.84×10²C",
        "8.24×10²C",
        "2.84×10²C"
      ]
    },
    "Answer": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "2.84×10²C"
    },
    "Explanation": {
      "type": "string",
      "content": "<p><b>Step 1:</b> Calculate moles of Cu:</p> \\[ n = \\frac{3g}{63.5g/mol} ≈ 0.0472mol \\] <p><b>Step 2:</b> Find number of atoms:</p> \\[ N = 0.0472 \\times 6.022\\times10^{23} ≈ 2.84\\times10^{22} \\] <p><b>Step 3:</b> Total electrons (29 per atom):</p> \\[ e^- = 29 \\times 2.84\\times10^{22} = 8.24\\times10^{23} \\] <p><b>Step 4:</b> Total charge (1e⁻ = 1.6×10⁻¹⁹C):</p> \\[ Q = 8.24\\times10^{23} \\times 1.6\\times10^{-19}C ≈ 1.32\\times10^5C \\] <p>Note: Options seem incorrect; recalculated value is ~1.32×10⁵C.</p>"
    },
    "topic": [
      "Physics",
      "Electromagnetism",
      "Electric Charge",
      "Electrostatics",
      "Atomic Structure"
    ]
  }
